      "role": "user",
      "content": "the \"magical\" part is what's tripping me up. i keep hearing people call it \"spooky action at a distance\"—can you explain why that term is used? it sounds like there's something more to it than just the twin analogy.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was initially skeptical of quantum mechanics. He felt that the idea of particles being connected across vast distances, influencing each other instantaneously, was too far-fetched to be explained by classical physics. Einstein's concern was that this phenomenon seemed to defy the fundamental principles of space and time, which he believed should govern the behavior of physical systems.\n\nThe term \"spooky\" was meant to convey the sense of unease and discomfort that Einstein felt about this aspect of quantum mechanics. It's not that the phenomenon is literally \"spooky\" in the sense of being supernatural or paranormal, but rather that it challenges our intuitive understanding of the world.\n\nIn essence, the term \"spooky action at a distance\" highlights the fact that entanglement seems to operate outside of the classical notion of space and time, where cause and effect are typically linked by a causal chain. Instead, entangled particles can affect each other instantaneously, regardless of the distance between them, which seems to blur the boundaries between space and time.\n\nIt's worth noting that the term \"spooky action at a distance\" has since become a widely accepted term in the physics community, and it's often",
